data.content:
You're already set — **no wrapper needs to be generated**. 🎉

Your code already uses `IFileSystem` from the **System.IO.Abstractions** NuGet package, which is the recommended, battle-tested abstraction for file system testability. A custom wrapper would be redundant.

You just need to make sure your DI and test projects are wired up:

**DI registration** (in `Program.cs` / `Startup.cs`):
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**Testing** (install the helper package):
```
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data.txt", new MockFileData("hello") }
});
var service = new DataService(mockFs);
Assert.Equal("hello", service.ReadData("/data.txt"));
```

Nothing else to generate here — `System.IO.Abstractions` already provides the interface, default implementation, and mock.
